  "summary": "Following the death of Hinata-ko, Motoshige (Motsu) experienced declining health and loneliness, eventually calling his long-estranged sons back to Inabu Castle. Motsu passed away one month prior to the current events, an occurrence Mukai compares to the decline of the Ashikaga shogunate disrupting a long-standing equilibrium. Following Motsu's death, Yodo, Uma, and Kouzu were also killed.\n\nDiscussions regarding the Mikage family tree reveal the existence of a missing woman named Uzuki, identified as Mutōmochi's youngest daughter. She reportedly ran away with a man thirty years ago, an act of \"selfishness\" that led Dōshō to sever all ties with her. This is contrasted with her cousin Kujaku, who chose true love, and Kusunoki, who failed to obtain what he wanted.\n\nRegarding the recent murders, Mochizuki proposes a new suspect: Hiruko or her descendants. This theory suggests the killer might be an outsider, a possibility that would disrupt the current investigation and potentially implicate everyone from the protagonists to Detective Tsujimura and the police.\n\nLater, the group visits Yoshino, who is listening to a melancholy piano quintet by the Russian composer Mikhail Ivanovich Medtner. Kumagai explains that Medtner was a figure \"erased from history\" because the Bolsheviks destroyed his compositions following the Russian Revolution. It is noted that Medtner was a political figure rumored to have plotted with Rasputin. The conversation concludes with a mention of Sergei Prokofiev, who lived in Japan during his exile.",
